{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01BNN6P8j4G9CRGXQcqeyigR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Line 509-510 says \"Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the finalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\" This is now slightly misleading because the code now uses `WorseState` to combine main and finalize outcomes. The overall run state now reflects the worst of main and finalize, not just the main result.\n\nHowever, this text is talking about the workflow DSL wiring, not the run state propagation. The wiring to `done` means the step itself completes (as opposed to aborting the workflow). The run state of the finalize step is still factored in. \n\nLooking back at the actual implementation, the finalize function returns a `*RunResult` and `overallState` combines both main and finalize states using `WorseState`, so a failed finalize step does affect the final outcome. The USAGE.md comment about wiring to `done` is accurate at the DSL level—it ensures the workflow completes normally rather than aborting—but it doesn't capture that the overall state now reflects whether finalize succeeded or failed. I need to clarify the USAGE.md documentation to reflect that the finalize phase's outcome now does affect the overall workflow status, since the daemon combines run states from both phases when computing the final result.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1466,"cache_read_input_tokens":24087,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1466},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b7063410-9e81-4bdd-a303-eb35e073d3d0","uuid":"513114df-e95d-44bc-bd33-5ec56d4e11d2"}
